            },
            " over the ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "centre",
                "value": "centre"
            },
            " but maintaining as much flexibility as possible by deferring ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "committing pawns",
                "value": "pawn_structures"
            },
            " to occupy it right away.",
            "\n\nDeveloping the queenside knight, in contrast, would block in ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "the c-pawn",
                "value": "using_the_c_pawn"
            },
            " making it slightly less useful than its counterpart if the opening ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "transposes",
                "value": "transposition"
            },
            " into a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "queen's pawn",
                "value": "the_centre_pawns"
            },
            " game."
        ]
    },
    "e4": {
        "description": [
            "White begins with a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "King's Pawn Opening",
                "value": "the_centre_pawns",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " grabbing ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "space",
                "value": "space"
            },
            " and making a play for ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "control",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " of the ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "centre",
                "value": "centre",
                "punctuation": "."
            },
            "\nPushing the king's pawn also ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "opens up",
                "value": "piece_vision"
            },
            " the kingside bishop, facilitating the option of rapid kingside castling."
        ],
        "e5": {
            "description": [
                "Black mirrors, choosing the least confrontational way to take space and presence in the centre for",
                " themselves in response."
            ],
            "Nf3": {
                "description": [
                    "White ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "develops",
                        "value": "development"
                    },
                    " a knight out towards the centre, exerting more influence there and simultaneously",
                    " threatening the e5 pawn.",
                    "\nDeveloping the kingside knight rather than the queenside knight maintains White's lead in",
                    " progress towards castling, which ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_italic",
                        "text": "can"
                    },
                    " build into an ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "advantage",
                        "value": "king_safety"
                    },
                    " if Black falls too far behind."
                ],
                "Nc6": {
                    "description": [
                        "Black develops a knight of their own to also further cover the centre, choosing the more stable",
                        " of the two options as this adds a defender to the e5 pawn."
                    ],
                    "Bc4": {
                        "title": "Italian Game",
                        "description": [
                            "White develops their light-squared bishop, choosing a spot which has great presence in the",
                            " centre while being difficult to immediately harass, and adds pressure to the ",
                            {
                                "type": "glossary_button",
                                "text": "weak f7 square",
                                "value": "the_f_pawn",
                                "punctuation": "."
                            },
                            "\n\nBy developing both kingside minor pieces first, White is now ready to castle."
                        ],
                        "h6": {
                            "annotation": "?!",
                            "title": "Italian Game: Anti-Fried Liver Defence",
                            "description": [
                                "Black ",
                                {
                                    "type": "glossary_button",
                                    "text": "denies",
                                    "value": "prophylaxis"
                                },
                                " the g5 square to White by covering it with the h-pawn. This prevents ",
                                {
                                    "type": "wrap_bold",
                                    "text": "Ng5"
                                },
                                " as would be played in certain lines such as this ",
                                {
                                    "type": "set_moves_button",
                                    "text": "alternative",
                                    "value": ["e4", "e5", "Nf3", "Nc6", "Bc4", "Nf6", "Ng5"],
                                    "punctuation": ","
                                },
                                " the aim of which is to add pressure to the f7 square generating a serious threat.",
                                "\n\nAlthough it prevents a clear plan of White's, this move unnecessarily delays crucial",
                                " development. There are other options available to handle White's potential offensive",
                                " which do not delay development (for example ",
                                {
                                    "type": "set_moves_button",
                                    "text": "this",
                                    "value": "e4 e5 Nf3 Nc6 Bc4 Bc5 d3 Nf6 Ng5 O-O"
                                },
                                " line) and as such this move is slightly inaccurate at the engine level.",
                                "\n\nWhite can best punish this by ",
                                {
                                    "type": "glossary_button",
                                    "text": "cracking open",
                                    "value": "pawn_breaks"
                                },
                                " the centre to expose the kings with ",
                                {
                                    "type": "set_moves_button",
                                    "text": "d4",
                                    "value": "e4 e5 Nf3 Nc6 Bc4 h6 d4",
                                    "punctuation": ","
                                },
                                " playing on Black's inability to castle due to the undeveloped kingside knight and bishop",
                                " while White enjoys the privilege of being able to castle their own king to safety at a",
                                " moment's notice.",
                                "\nAlternatively, castling first and then playing d4 on the ",
                                {
                                    "type": "set_moves_button",
                                    "text": "next move",
                                    "value": "e4 e5 Nf3 Nc6 Bc4 h6 O-O Nf6 d4"
                                },
                                " is also a very strong response for White to play."
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    },
    "d4": {
        "description": [
            "White begins with a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "Queen's Pawn Opening",
                "value": "the_centre_pawns",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " grabbing ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "space",
                "value": "space"
            },
            " and making a play for ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "control",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " of the ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "centre",
                "value": "centre",
                "punctuation": "."
            }
        ],
        "d5": {
            "description": [
                "Black mirrors, choosing the least confrontational way to take space and presence in the centre for",
                " themselves in response."
            ],
            "c4": {
                "title": "Queen's Gambit",
                "description": [
                    "White immediately challenges Black's pawn on d5. This ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "gambit",
                        "value": "gambits"
                    },
                    " offers up ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "the c-pawn",
                        "value": "using_the_c_pawn",
                        "punctuation": ","
                    },
                    " tempting Black to give up central control by capturing it.",
                    "\nIf Black accepts, White has the opportunity to capitalise on this ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "imbalance",
                        "value": "imbalances"
                    },
                    " by seizing control of the centre with a move like ",
                    {
                        "type": "add_moves_button",
                        "text": "e4",
                        "value": ["dxc4", "e4"]
                    },
                    " or ",
                    {
                        "type": "add_moves_button",
                        "text": "Nf3",
                        "value": ["dxc4", "Nf3"],
                        "punctuation": "."
                    },
                    "\n\nAs this move also clears a diagonal for the queen, if Black accepts the gambit it is ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_italic",
                        "text": "possible"
                    },
                    " to immediately win the pawn back with ",
                    {
                        "type": "add_moves_button",
                        "text": "Qa4+",
                        "value": ["dxc4", "Qa4+"],
                        "punctuation": ","
                    },
                    " ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "forking",
                        "value": "forks"
                    },
                    " both Black's pawn and their king. This will however allow Black to reclaim their stake in the centre",
                    " by (for example) blocking the check with ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_bold",
                        "text": "Nc6"
                    },
                    ", nullifying the advantages of the gambit and leaving White with a slightly ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "misplaced",
                        "value": "positional_chess"
                    },
                    " queen.",
                    "\nDue to the pawn's tenuous position in White's territory if Black should capture, it is regardless",
                    " virtually impossible for Black to then defend it long-term (one of White's best followup moves, ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_bold",
                        "text": "e4"
                    },
                    ", would also immediately threaten to retake it with the ",
                    {
                        "type": "glossary_button",
                        "text": "now-unblocked",
                        "value": "discovered_attacks"
                    },
                    " bishop), rendering ",
                    {
                        "type": "wrap_bold",
                        "text": "Qa4+"
                    },
                    " entirely unnecessary."
                ],
                "e6": {
                    "title": "Queen's Gambit Declined",
                    "description": [
                        "Rather than accepting the gambit, Black reinforces their d-pawn with the e-pawn, attempting to",
                        " cement their place in the centre.",
                        "\nThis move limits White's ability to further encroach with ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "e4"
                        },
                        ",",
                        " by ensuring that a pawn will remain on d5 controlling the e4 square even if White ",
                        {
                            "type": "add_moves_button",
                            "text": "exchanges",
                            "value": ["cxd5", "exd5"]
                        },
                        " their c-pawn for it."
                    ]
                }
            }
        }
    }
